vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2016-10735
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap 3.x before 3.4.0 and 4.x-beta before 4.0.0-beta.2, XSS is possible in the data-target attribute, a different vulnerability than CVE-2018-14041.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2018-14041
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap before 4.1.2, XSS is possible in the data-target property of scrollspy.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2018-14042
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap before 4.1.2, XSS is possible in the data-container property of tooltip.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2018-20676
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap before 3.4.0, XSS is possible in the tooltip data-viewport attribute.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2018-20677
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap before 3.4.0, XSS is possible in the affix configuration target property.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2019-8331
vulnerabilities.description: In Bootstrap before 3.4.1 and 4.3.x before 4.3.1, XSS is possible in the tooltip or popover data-template attribute.

vulnerabilities.name: Bootstrap before 4.0.0 is end-of-life and no longer maintained.
vulnerabilities.description: Bootstrap before 4.0.0 is end-of-life and no longer maintained.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2019-11358
vulnerabilities.description: jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2020-11022
vulnerabilities.description: In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.2 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0.

vulnerabilities.name: CVE-2020-11023

knownExploitedVulnerability.Name: JQuery Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability
knownExploitedVulnerability.Description: JQuery contains a persistent cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerability. When passing maliciously formed, untrusted input enclosed in HTML tags, JQuery's DOM manipulators can execute untrusted code in the context of the user's browser.
knownExploitedVulnerability.RequiredAction: Apply mitigations per vendor instructions or discontinue use of the product if mitigations are unavailable.
knownExploitedVulnerability.Notes: This vulnerability could affect an open-source component, third-party library, protocol, or proprietary implementation that could be used by different products. For more information, please see: https://github.com/jquery/jquery/security/advisories/GHSA-jpcq-cgw6-v4j6 ; https://blog.jquery.com/2020/04/10/jquery-3-5-0-released/ ; https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2020-11023

vulnerabilities.description: In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.0.3 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML containing <option> elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0.
